176
00:14:03,220 --> 00:14:09,700
SPEAKER_00: Why is it that in finance, you can't pay to get better results like you can in every other area of life?

177
00:14:10,400 --> 00:14:20,960
SPEAKER_00: Bogle talked about that a lot but his point was that unlike other areas of life where paying more does come with the expectation of better results, paying higher investment fees typically results in lower returns, not higher.

178
00:14:21,780 --> 00:14:25,720
SPEAKER_00: Vanguard also has research similar to Morningstar showing the same kind of thing is true.

179
00:14:26,400 --> 00:14:32,520
SPEAKER_00: Bill Sharp in 1991 introduced this idea in an article of the arithmetic of active management.

180
00:14:33,180 --> 00:14:38,580
SPEAKER_00: He basically just said, I mean it's simple when you think about it, but it took a Nobel Laureate to come up with it I guess.

181
00:14:39,240 --> 00:14:46,520
SPEAKER_00: If active and passive management styles, so active is stock picking and market timing, passive is just owning the market, indexing.

182
00:14:46,880 --> 00:14:47,740
SPEAKER_00: total market indexing.

183
00:14:48,460 --> 00:14:58,760
SPEAKER_00: If active and passive management styles are defined in sensible ways, it must be the case that before costs, the return on the average actively managed dollar will equal the return on the average passively managed dollar.

184
00:14:59,420 --> 00:15:00,700
SPEAKER_00: They're both investing in the market.

185
00:15:01,680 --> 00:15:03,200
SPEAKER_00: In aggregate, active funds own the market.

186
00:15:03,460 --> 00:15:05,020
SPEAKER_00: In aggregate, passive funds own the market.

187
00:15:05,840 --> 00:15:06,760
SPEAKER_00: Before costs are the same.

188
00:15:07,420 --> 00:15:13,780
SPEAKER_00: After costs, the return on the average actively managed dollar will be less than the return on the average passively managed dollar.

189
00:15:14,180 --> 00:15:14,920
SPEAKER_00: It must be true.

190
00:15:15,600 --> 00:15:24,900
SPEAKER_00: If that is true, It suggests that in simple terms, in aggregate, investors and active funds, they must underperform investors in total market index funds because of the higher fees and costs.

191
00:15:25,320 --> 00:15:27,580
SPEAKER_00: It's pretty simple and pretty hard to argue with.

192
00:15:28,100 --> 00:15:29,040
SPEAKER_02: It's a great little paper too.

193
00:15:29,400 --> 00:15:30,700
SPEAKER_02: It's like two pages long or something.

194
00:15:31,120 --> 00:15:32,060
SPEAKER_00: Yeah, it's a short little article.

195
00:15:32,200 --> 00:15:33,200
SPEAKER_00: It's not an academic paper.

196
00:15:33,320 --> 00:15:36,340
SPEAKER_00: It's in a journal, but I don't think it was posted in there as a peer reviewed.

197
00:15:36,860 --> 00:15:40,140
SPEAKER_00: I don't know actually if it was peer reviewed, but it was a short little write up on.

198
00:15:40,220 --> 00:15:41,080
SPEAKER_00: this must be true.

199
00:15:41,800 --> 00:15:43,300
SPEAKER_01: On a dollar weighted basis, of course.

200
00:15:43,740 --> 00:15:51,080
SPEAKER_01: It doesn't mean that All active investors must underperform all passive investors, but in aggregate.

201
00:15:51,380 --> 00:15:52,580
SPEAKER_01: That's the key, I think.

202
00:15:53,020 --> 00:16:02,080
SPEAKER_01: And a lot of people have picked on that point and said, it sounds like Sharpe is arguing that it's essentially impossible to outperform, but of course that's not what he said.

203
00:16:02,180 --> 00:16:06,260
SPEAKER_01: And it's still been a fairly controversial argument over the years, hasn't it?

204
00:16:06,480 --> 00:16:14,140
SPEAKER_01: There's been a lot of pushback against it, but at its very basic core, it is just arithmetic.

205
00:16:14,900 --> 00:16:15,200
SPEAKER_00: It is.

206
00:16:15,700 --> 00:16:16,620
SPEAKER_00: You're right, it's controversial.

207
00:16:16,680 --> 00:16:19,560
SPEAKER_00: There's a paper called Sharpening Sharpe's Arithmetic that kind of argues with it.

208
00:16:19,920 --> 00:16:23,780
SPEAKER_00: Mike Green brought that paper up when he was on our podcast and talked about what the flaws are.

209
00:16:24,180 --> 00:16:33,820
SPEAKER_00: I think there may even be a footnote that Mike Green refers to about I think ignores flows, Sharpe's Arithmetic does and he's like, well, there are flows, so it's wrong.

210
00:16:34,600 --> 00:16:47,880
SPEAKER_00: The thing about it is, we can argue about the assumptions or whatever, but multiple academic studies in top journals by top academics, found Sharpe's Arithmetic to be approximately, maybe not totally true, but close enough.

211
00:16:48,600 --> 00:16:54,540
SPEAKER_00: Before fees, there is evidence in a lot of these studies that active funds do actually add a bit of value on average.

212
00:16:55,080 --> 00:17:02,220
SPEAKER_00: But net of fees, which is obviously what matters to investors, all credible studies agree that the average active fund is not adding value.

213
00:17:02,780 --> 00:17:04,079
SPEAKER_00: There may be room for pre-fee.

214
00:17:04,160 --> 00:17:06,540
SPEAKER_00: Hey, there's some neat stuff going on in there, but net of fees.

215
00:17:07,859 --> 00:17:15,420
SPEAKER_00: Burke and Green 2004 paper kind of argues that mutual fund managers are skilled, but all of their skill is absorbed by their fees.

216
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:20,300
SPEAKER_00: That's their theory of market efficiency in the market for manager skill.

217
00:17:20,640 --> 00:17:23,280
SPEAKER_00: The other thing that's important here is that it's not just fees.

218
00:17:23,720 --> 00:17:26,540
SPEAKER_00: Investors in a fund pay transaction costs.

219
00:17:27,079 --> 00:17:36,680
SPEAKER_00: In Canada, funds have to report a portion of transaction costs, the explicit costs, not the implicit costs, which is another potentially important cost, but the explicit costs are reported.

220
00:17:37,460 --> 00:17:44,020
SPEAKER_00: the trading expense ratio, the TER, which you can find in the MRFP and the manager report of fund performance for any fund.

221
00:17:44,480 --> 00:17:48,060
SPEAKER_00: Index funds tend to have very low trading expense ratios, often rounding to 0%.

222
00:17:49,200 --> 00:17:53,540
SPEAKER_00: When I wrote this video, I did go and check several index funds to make sure that what I was saying was true.

223
00:17:54,100 --> 00:17:55,860
SPEAKER_00: I kind of knew that, but I wanted to be sure.

224
00:17:56,160 --> 00:17:58,980
SPEAKER_00: They typically are very close or actually are 0%.

225
00:17:59,340 --> 00:18:03,060
SPEAKER_00: Actively managed funds, because they trade more, they're going to tend to have higher trading costs.

226
00:18:03,660 --> 00:18:04,760
SPEAKER_00: This is kind of a crazy stat.

227
00:18:05,240 --> 00:18:12,640
SPEAKER_00: It's not uncommon for the trading cost of an actively managed fund to be higher than an index fund's fees and trading costs combined.

228
00:18:13,020 --> 00:18:14,800
SPEAKER_01: I would think that's fairly common.

229
00:18:15,160 --> 00:18:15,460
SPEAKER_00: It is.

230
00:18:15,880 --> 00:18:20,700
SPEAKER_01: For a traditional index fund that might cost five or six basis points and that's it.

231
00:18:20,980 --> 00:18:21,720
SPEAKER_01: That's the MER.

232
00:18:21,820 --> 00:18:24,380
SPEAKER_01: There's virtually zero trading expense ratio.

233
00:18:24,940 --> 00:18:27,800
SPEAKER_01: Many mutual funds are going to be much, much more than that.

234
00:18:28,280 --> 00:18:31,100
SPEAKER_00: I always send my scripts to Ray who I work with at PWL.

235
00:18:31,700 --> 00:18:36,300
SPEAKER_00: just because he's very smart and gives me a great second set of eyes before I start recording and stuff like that.

236
00:18:36,720 --> 00:18:41,300
SPEAKER_00: That's one of the things that came back as a piece of feedback was, are you sure about that?

237
00:18:41,560 --> 00:18:42,640
SPEAKER_00: Do you have data to back that up?

238
00:18:43,180 --> 00:18:44,980
SPEAKER_00: So I was like, oh, all right, I better get some data.

239
00:18:45,060 --> 00:18:48,920
SPEAKER_00: So I went and pulled a bunch of MRFPs for active funds to back up what I said.

240
00:18:49,460 --> 00:18:53,240
SPEAKER_00: I did indeed find that it was not uncommon for that to be true, but it is crazy.

241
00:18:54,020 --> 00:18:58,280
SPEAKER_02: It gets even crazier when you get into some of these niche funds that are using options strategies and stuff.

242
00:18:58,420 --> 00:19:02,920
SPEAKER_02: I've seen TERs in the two to three percent range for some of the really, really niche stuff.

243
00:19:03,520 --> 00:19:10,020
SPEAKER_02: It's not as well advertised as the MER management ratio, so a lot of investors don't even know they're paying those fees, and they can be very high.

244
00:19:10,600 --> 00:19:22,940
SPEAKER_01: Yeah, you'll sometimes see that show up in things like the swap-based ETFs, for example, that they pay a fee and then that's not reflected in the MER, which is a little deceptive because it's known ahead of time what that fee's going to be.

245
00:19:23,800 --> 00:19:25,200
SPEAKER_01: and it's buried as a TER.

246
00:19:25,680 --> 00:19:28,940
SPEAKER_01: Currency hedging I think will show up as a TER as well.

247
00:19:29,620 --> 00:19:42,820
SPEAKER_01: There's a lot of times where when you're looking at the MER, it looks superficially low but if you scratch the surface, you realize there are other costs there that are going to show up and are going to erode your returns the same way an MER will.

248
00:19:43,660 --> 00:19:49,800
SPEAKER_00: Yeah, cost that show up in net returns but don't necessarily show up when you're trying to evaluate the costs, at least not in a way that's easy to see.

249
00:19:50,680 --> 00:19:52,380
SPEAKER_00: You brought this up or you alluded to this earlier, Dan.

250
00:19:52,740 --> 00:19:59,960
SPEAKER_00: As important as fees and costs are, which is really important, a lot of people are not aware that low cost are one of the benefits of index funds.

251
00:20:00,500 --> 00:20:11,780
SPEAKER_00: There's a survey by the OSC that was done in 2022 and they found that only 31% of Canadian respondents were aware that index funds have lower fees and expenses than actively managed funds.

252
00:20:12,320 --> 00:20:12,480
SPEAKER_00: Wow.

253
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:13,540
SPEAKER_01: It's pretty low.

254
00:20:14,260 --> 00:20:22,060
SPEAKER_01: I will say too, if you go back, when I started doing my blog in 2010, it was significantly lower than that.

255
00:20:22,140 --> 00:20:25,640
SPEAKER_01: I don't have data for that, but anecdotally, I'm pretty confident it was lower.

256
00:20:26,140 --> 00:20:33,500
SPEAKER_01: I mean, at least we can celebrate that it's up to 31%, but hopefully we can get that to 91% at some point.

257
00:20:33,980 --> 00:20:40,420
SPEAKER_01: Because make your choice, but if you're going to make a choice about what strategy to use, you need to know the basic information.

258
00:20:40,500 --> 00:20:50,220
SPEAKER_01: And the fact that less than a third of people even understand that they're cheaper, let alone the enormous outperformance of index funds in aggregate over active funds.

259
00:20:50,580 --> 00:20:54,480
SPEAKER_01: Just not even knowing that they're cheaper is pretty surprising.

260
00:20:54,540 --> 00:20:55,540
SPEAKER_01: that the number is that low.

261
00:20:56,220 --> 00:20:58,800
SPEAKER_02: Well, it probably only got to 31% because of your blog, Dan.

262
00:20:59,240 --> 00:21:01,840
SPEAKER_02: You're probably responsible for at least half of those 31 respondents.

263
00:21:02,060 --> 00:21:02,840
SPEAKER_00: That's probably true.

264
00:21:03,620 --> 00:21:04,560
SPEAKER_01: I hope that's the case.

265
00:21:04,960 --> 00:21:14,160
SPEAKER_01: I have certainly noticed it over the years that if I go back and read those old comments and even some of the old blogs, it's just pretty shocking how far we have come.

266
00:21:14,580 --> 00:21:16,400
SPEAKER_01: We're moving in the right direction for sure.

267
00:21:17,120 --> 00:21:18,020
SPEAKER_00: Fees are not the only reason.

268
00:21:18,260 --> 00:21:19,080
SPEAKER_00: That's one big reason.

269
00:21:19,360 --> 00:21:20,600
SPEAKER_00: It's one that people should be aware of.

270
00:21:21,220 --> 00:21:22,540
SPEAKER_00: I like that point about just awareness.

271
00:21:23,020 --> 00:21:28,220
SPEAKER_00: Mark, you were there and Dan, you listened to the Hendrik Bessembinder episode but he talked about how some people can have a preference for skewness.

272
00:21:28,740 --> 00:21:35,940
SPEAKER_00: If someone has all the information and they understand that outcomes are skewed and they understand the fees are high or whatever and they still want to invest in an active fund, great.

273
00:21:36,420 --> 00:21:41,800
SPEAKER_00: But they should make that decision understanding the stuff that we're talking about as opposed to not making it without understanding it.

274
00:21:42,680 --> 00:21:46,620
SPEAKER_00: Fees are not the only reason that actively managed funds will tend to underperform.

275
00:21:47,100 --> 00:21:58,000
SPEAKER_00: Their lack of diversification, and this is the Bessembinder stuff, also poses a challenge, which brings us to the next point in favor of index funds, which is that index funds are broadly diversified.

276
00:21:58,500 --> 00:22:04,340
SPEAKER_00: By replicating the returns of a market index, index funds hold a huge portion of the stocks in the market.

277
00:22:04,920 --> 00:22:12,060
SPEAKER_00: Now on the other hand, in their efforts to try and beat the market, actively managed funds will tend to hold fewer stocks, a lot fewer.

278
00:22:12,440 --> 00:22:13,400
SPEAKER_00: I don't remember what the number is.

279
00:22:13,680 --> 00:22:18,600
SPEAKER_00: Bessembinder has it in one of his papers, the average active mutual fund holdings, but it's low.

280
00:22:19,380 --> 00:22:30,100
SPEAKER_00: Portfolio concentration, thinking back to Bessem Binder, can be a good thing if a fund manager knows how to pick winning stocks, but picking winning stocks consistently is really, really hard.

281
00:22:30,320 --> 00:22:38,660
SPEAKER_00: We know that stock returns are positively skewed, which means that most stocks don't perform very well in the long run, while a relative few perform exceptionally well.

282
00:22:39,260 --> 00:22:42,920
SPEAKER_00: The result is that well, The long-term return of the overall market is positive.

283
00:22:43,100 --> 00:22:45,900
SPEAKER_00: The majority of individual stocks underperform.

284
00:22:46,600 --> 00:22:48,380
SPEAKER_00: I'm going to recount some of the Besson Binder data.

285
00:22:48,520 --> 00:22:50,960
SPEAKER_00: Anybody that listened last week has already heard this recently.

286
00:22:51,520 --> 00:23:00,900
SPEAKER_00: In the sample from 1926 through 2016, 42.6% of US stocks had lifetime buy and hold returns that exceeded one month US treasury bills.

287
00:23:01,540 --> 00:23:02,700
SPEAKER_00: Pretty crazy, less than half.

288
00:23:03,040 --> 00:23:06,400
SPEAKER_00: Just over 50% of US stocks had negative lifetime returns.

289
00:23:06,980 --> 00:23:17,760
SPEAKER_00: About 12% of US stocks lost 100% of their value over their lifetime and only 30.8% of stocks in the US market generate a lifetime buy and hold returns that beat the market.

290
00:23:18,480 --> 00:23:25,520
SPEAKER_01: You blew through those numbers pretty fast Ben but I think it is worth taking a deep breath and thinking about them because they are mind blowing.

291
00:23:25,920 --> 00:23:36,100
SPEAKER_01: This idea that barely half of stocks in the US had positive returns, not market beating returns, just not negative.

292
00:23:36,840 --> 00:23:41,660
SPEAKER_01: What does that mean for the fortunes of people who are picking individual stocks?

293
00:23:42,180 --> 00:23:47,700
SPEAKER_01: Let's take a minute to think about what happens if you instead own thousands of stocks.

294
00:23:48,280 --> 00:23:51,740
SPEAKER_01: You're still going to see half of them deliver negative returns.

295
00:23:52,380 --> 00:23:57,300
SPEAKER_01: But historically, you're still going to see market returns by holding the whole market surprise.

296
00:23:57,820 --> 00:24:04,780
SPEAKER_01: But the point is, even with those 50% underperformers in there, long-term stock market returns have been outstanding.

297
00:24:04,920 --> 00:24:11,240
SPEAKER_01: But once you start picking and choosing, the chances of you ending up with more negatives than positive is very high.

298
00:24:11,880 --> 00:24:16,080
SPEAKER_01: To me, this is just a slam dunk argument for broad diversification.

299
00:24:16,760 --> 00:24:27,020
SPEAKER_02: Picking from that 31% of stocks that generated positive buy and hold returns, the additional excess returns that they generate have to be enough to at least offset the ones that you picked from the bad pile, from the bad 50%.

300
00:24:27,540 --> 00:24:38,220
SPEAKER_02: So even if you do capture a few of those great stocks, you're more likely to have captured the ones that drove negative returns and those negative returns can drive your entire portfolio down such that you earn less than market returns over time.

301
00:24:38,580 --> 00:24:46,360
SPEAKER_02: I just don't understand why people go through the exercise of doing this when the data to me is just so obviously overwhelming in favor of not doing it.

302
00:24:46,940 --> 00:24:48,720
SPEAKER_01: Because they prefer skewness.

303
00:24:49,440 --> 00:24:49,940
SPEAKER_02: Absolutely.

304
00:24:51,180 --> 00:24:52,720
SPEAKER_01: It's an interesting way of putting it.

305
00:24:53,020 --> 00:25:00,540
SPEAKER_01: It's essentially saying people prefer a low probability activity with negative expected value.

306
00:25:00,860 --> 00:25:06,160
SPEAKER_01: So great, I'm glad you had that preference but that's not a preference that I would promote to anybody.

307
00:25:07,040 --> 00:25:10,900
SPEAKER_00: I'd also say that's an educated or a relatively educated way of doing it.

308
00:25:11,280 --> 00:25:13,240
SPEAKER_00: We talked about this a bit with best reminder too.

309
00:25:13,900 --> 00:25:15,200
SPEAKER_00: A lot of it is just overconfidence.

310
00:25:15,480 --> 00:25:17,100
SPEAKER_00: They don't think that they've got a skewness preference.

311
00:25:17,140 --> 00:25:19,260
SPEAKER_00: They think that they're for sure going to beat the market.

312
00:25:19,920 --> 00:25:21,020
SPEAKER_00: The skewness preference is interesting.

313
00:25:21,480 --> 00:25:25,040
SPEAKER_00: On the coffee's ill video that I did, I looked at some of the comments.

314
00:25:25,080 --> 00:25:34,300
SPEAKER_00: I see this on my videos sometimes too where some people say, that's all great but don't have enough money for index funds to matter, I need one big win.

315
00:25:34,680 --> 00:25:40,020
SPEAKER_00: They feel like they need to win the lottery to have any chance of financial success, which is a pretty scary proposition when you think about it.

316
00:25:40,660 --> 00:25:43,980
SPEAKER_00: Most stocks don't beat the market and the data for global stocks are actually even worse.

317
00:25:44,420 --> 00:25:47,780
SPEAKER_00: The skewness is even worse and that's again based on best in mind or stuff.

318
00:25:48,340 --> 00:26:00,040
SPEAKER_00: Now, if a fund manager can identify there's relatively few winners ahead of time, they are obviously going to generate higher returns but as you were just saying Mark, they're much more likely to end up with losers than winners.

319
00:26:00,800 --> 00:26:03,240
SPEAKER_00: Index funds are always going to hold the winners.

320
00:26:03,780 --> 00:26:06,020
SPEAKER_00: That's why on average, they come out ahead.

321
00:26:06,360 --> 00:26:13,160
SPEAKER_00: Free Bessem binder, there was a 2017 paper called Why Indexing Works, I covered in a video years ago.

322
00:26:13,820 --> 00:26:25,340
SPEAKER_00: It does like a model of, okay, if we assume stock returns are skewed, it doesn't quantify them empirically the way a Bessem binder does, but it just kind of says, if stock returns are skewed, what does that mean for active versus passive performance?

323
00:26:25,480 --> 00:26:34,800
SPEAKER_00: It shows in this relatively simple model why You have a small chance of outperforming by a lot, but you're much more likely to underperform with active because of that skewness.

324
00:26:35,380 --> 00:26:40,180
SPEAKER_00: That brings us to the next point in favor of index funds, which is investment returns.

325
00:26:40,520 --> 00:26:44,540
SPEAKER_00: Index funds beat the vast majority of active funds and the average active fund.

326
00:26:44,980 --> 00:26:47,860
SPEAKER_00: In a 2023 study, this is again Bessembinder.

327
00:26:48,420 --> 00:26:56,440
SPEAKER_00: You can listen last week if you want to hear him add more color to it, but he looks at long-term returns for US equity mutual funds from 1991 through 2020.

328
00:26:57,280 --> 00:27:03,880
SPEAKER_00: They find that Most funds by number underperform an index fund, they use SPY, even before fees.

329
00:27:04,160 --> 00:27:05,520
SPEAKER_00: That stat I find crazy.

330
00:27:05,760 --> 00:27:15,740
SPEAKER_00: Before the mutual fund fees, most funds by count, not by asset weighted average, just by number of funds, most of them underperform SPY pre-fee.

331
00:27:16,240 --> 00:27:17,580
SPEAKER_00: That shows the skewness.

332
00:27:17,700 --> 00:27:25,280
SPEAKER_00: Again, multiple studies, as I mentioned earlier, including the best and better one, find that the average active fund does slightly outperform before fees.

333
00:27:25,900 --> 00:27:27,680
SPEAKER_00: The average, the average dollar in funds.

334
00:27:28,240 --> 00:27:35,500
SPEAKER_00: But this study is showing that most funds, 54.8% of them underperform an index fund even before their fees are considered.

335
00:27:36,360 --> 00:27:36,800
SPEAKER_00: Pretty crazy.

336
00:27:37,460 --> 00:27:40,100
SPEAKER_00: I think the explanation is probably skewness.

337
00:27:40,740 --> 00:27:42,600
SPEAKER_00: We've got that crazy skewness in stock returns.

338
00:27:43,160 --> 00:27:46,560
SPEAKER_00: It's just much more likely for an active fund to pick losers than winners.

339
00:27:47,560 --> 00:27:53,900
SPEAKER_00: After fees, 30.3% of US equity mutual funds beat SPY over the full sample.

340
00:27:53,940 --> 00:27:56,900
SPEAKER_00: That number is a lot higher than something like the SPIVA report.

341
00:27:57,480 --> 00:27:58,980
SPEAKER_00: We did talk to Bessenbinder about that.

342
00:27:59,360 --> 00:28:03,280
SPEAKER_00: He's comparing to SPY, which has a fees and costs, but pretty low.

343
00:28:03,700 --> 00:28:05,780
SPEAKER_01: Well, three basis points or something like that.

344
00:28:06,240 --> 00:28:22,580
SPEAKER_00: Maybe a bit higher going back to earlier in the sample, but Bessenbinder talked about the SPIVA methodology, the way that they're treating funds that close, but didn't necessarily perform poorly, maybe part of the reason, something like that, but it's just a methodological difference.

345
00:28:23,300 --> 00:28:25,700
SPEAKER_01: That number seems a lot higher than I would have expected to.

346
00:28:26,540 --> 00:28:28,200
SPEAKER_01: It does raise an interesting point too.

347
00:28:28,680 --> 00:28:34,120
SPEAKER_01: You were saying earlier, Ben, that active funds will typically be less diversified than index funds.

348
00:28:34,460 --> 00:28:35,800
SPEAKER_01: And that's really by design.

349
00:28:35,920 --> 00:28:39,080
SPEAKER_01: It's not necessarily a flaw that they didn't notice.

350
00:28:39,160 --> 00:28:47,240
SPEAKER_01: The whole point is if you want to achieve market returns, you need to build a portfolio that doesn't look exactly like the market.

351
00:28:47,840 --> 00:28:50,460
SPEAKER_01: And the easiest way to do that is reduce the number of holdings.

352
00:28:51,060 --> 00:28:55,100
SPEAKER_01: That is where you give yourself at least a chance about performance.

353
00:28:55,840 --> 00:29:07,580
SPEAKER_01: As you know, one of the biggest challenges in mutual funds is so many of them are fearful of underperforming the benchmark too much, so they just hold more and more stocks.

354
00:29:07,620 --> 00:29:17,720
SPEAKER_01: They look more and more like the index and it leads to what they call closet indexing, whereas it's masquerading as an actively managed fund, but it has a makeup very similar to the index.

355
00:29:17,840 --> 00:29:21,700
SPEAKER_01: The only difference is instead of charging five basis points, it charges 90.

356
00:29:22,820 --> 00:29:24,280
SPEAKER_01: Your chances of outperformance?

357
00:29:25,120 --> 00:29:27,180
SPEAKER_01: a fund like that or effectively zero?

358
00:29:27,220 --> 00:29:29,860
SPEAKER_02: Well, that's where active share comes from essentially, right?

359
00:29:29,900 --> 00:29:33,080
SPEAKER_02: It's trying to measure that difference from the index, how active is the fund.

360
00:29:33,160 --> 00:29:39,680
SPEAKER_00: The guy who came up with that, I've emailed with him about coming on, rash reminder, he's done some more recent research on factor funds.

361
00:29:40,200 --> 00:29:42,600
SPEAKER_00: that was in progress when I talked to him, so he wanted to wait until that was done.

362
00:29:43,080 --> 00:29:46,560
SPEAKER_00: Martin Cramer, I don't know how to say his last name but yeah, that would be a good guess.

363
00:29:47,020 --> 00:29:54,220
SPEAKER_00: I have seen some stuff in Vanguard on more concentrated portfolios, not necessarily performing better but having much wider dispersion.

364
00:29:54,560 --> 00:30:02,840
SPEAKER_00: If you sort funds by more concentrated versus more diversified, to your point Dan, more diversified funds just look like the index, pretty much all of them underperformed by their fees.

365
00:30:03,420 --> 00:30:08,320
SPEAKER_00: When you go to the other end of the spectrum, more concentrated, you have some funds that do really well and some funds that do really poorly.

366
00:30:08,660 --> 00:30:10,380
SPEAKER_00: On average, they still kind of suck.

367
00:30:10,980 --> 00:30:17,700
SPEAKER_00: But if you want a shot at really good performance and you're willing to take on the risk of really bad performance, then yeah, more concentrated portfolio.

368
00:30:18,320 --> 00:30:19,040
SPEAKER_01: I think you need to.

369
00:30:19,400 --> 00:30:27,840
SPEAKER_01: If you're making an educated decision to be an active investor, You need to concentrate because if you don't, you're going to face all the problems we just talked about.

370
00:30:28,300 --> 00:30:35,100
SPEAKER_01: All the research on the skewness, for example, really highlights the additional risk you're taking by concentrating.

371
00:30:36,180 --> 00:30:36,580
SPEAKER_00: Exactly.

372
00:30:37,480 --> 00:30:51,420
SPEAKER_00: The SPIVA data that we mentioned, just to put some context to that, for the 20 years ending June 2024, the SPIVA report finds that fewer than 6% of US equity mutual funds in their sample beat the S&P composite 1500 index.

373
00:30:52,340 --> 00:30:56,800
SPEAKER_00: Lots of differences between that and the Bessenbinder finding but yeah, much worse in that case.

374
00:30:57,460 --> 00:31:07,880
SPEAKER_00: Academic papers, the original, the OG 1968 paper that introduced the idea of evaluating mutual fund returns on a risk adjusted basis and this is the paper where we get the term alpha.

375
00:31:08,540 --> 00:31:10,640
SPEAKER_00: It's Michael Jensen's paper, he calls it.

376
00:31:10,700 --> 00:31:11,640
SPEAKER_00: It's called Jensen's Alpha.

377
00:31:12,100 --> 00:31:13,980
SPEAKER_00: This is the paper that comes from which I think is pretty cool.

378
00:31:14,440 --> 00:31:15,320
SPEAKER_00: Highly cited paper.

379
00:31:15,360 --> 00:31:18,260
SPEAKER_00: I can't remember what the number is but it's like crazy number of citations.

380
00:31:18,740 --> 00:31:27,980
SPEAKER_00: That paper found that 115 mutual fund managers in the period 1945 to 64 were on average not able to outperform the market.

381
00:31:28,540 --> 00:31:34,560
SPEAKER_00: There was actually little evidence that any individual fund was able to do significantly better than what we would expect from random chance.

382
00:31:35,200 --> 00:31:42,880
SPEAKER_00: Then Fama and French have a big paper, also highly cited one, where they find that net of fees, the average US equity active fund underperforms.

383
00:31:43,640 --> 00:31:52,880
SPEAKER_00: again, the distribution of fund returns is in line with what we should expect by random chance before fees, but discouragingly worse when the higher fees of actively managed funds are taken into account.

384
00:31:53,640 --> 00:31:59,920
SPEAKER_00: Then there's a 2014 paper that looks at global equity funds and it comes to similar conclusions to the past papers.

385
00:32:00,420 --> 00:32:11,660
SPEAKER_00: Active management is basically a zero sum game before fees and it's a negative sum game after fees, maybe slightly before zero sum because a lot of these papers do find a little bit of pre-fee performance on average.

386
00:32:12,100 --> 00:32:15,160
SPEAKER_00: even if most funds are underperforming as we see from the Bessenbinder paper.

387
00:32:15,620 --> 00:32:19,920
SPEAKER_00: Together, all those data, there's the academic papers, there's industry data, there's lots of different ways.

388
00:32:19,960 --> 00:32:27,400
SPEAKER_00: this has been sliced but they all kind of agree that you're much more likely to underperform than to outperform by investing in an actively managed fund.

389
00:32:28,060 --> 00:32:29,880
SPEAKER_00: But there is a small chance of picking a big winner.

390
00:32:30,340 --> 00:32:34,780
SPEAKER_00: That's one of the funny things that Bessenbinder talked about is how his research has been used on both sides.

391
00:32:35,080 --> 00:32:41,640
SPEAKER_00: It's been used to support indexing but it's also been used to support active management because the active managers are like, hey look, We're going to be one of these ones.

392
00:32:42,140 --> 00:32:42,660
SPEAKER_00: It's kind of funny.

393
00:32:43,320 --> 00:32:53,240
SPEAKER_01: That's the argument I think that's been circulating forever because we all know that the chance of outperformance with active management is not zero.

394
00:32:53,540 --> 00:32:55,120
SPEAKER_01: It's some smaller number.

395
00:32:55,820 --> 00:32:58,300
SPEAKER_01: Everyone thinks they're part of that small number.

396
00:32:59,180 --> 00:33:05,920
SPEAKER_01: Unless you can somehow prove that it's theoretically impossible to ever beat the market, there will always be something to hold on to.

397
00:33:06,720 --> 00:33:08,940
SPEAKER_01: It's becoming increasingly tenuous, I think.

398
00:33:09,420 --> 00:33:10,180
SPEAKER_00: Yeah, I think so too.

399
00:33:10,780 --> 00:33:11,400
SPEAKER_02: What about Buffett?

400
00:33:11,820 --> 00:33:13,160
SPEAKER_02: That's the excuse everyone gives, right?

401
00:33:13,580 --> 00:33:14,900
SPEAKER_00: We already did an episode on that, Mark.

402
00:33:15,600 --> 00:33:15,780
SPEAKER_02: I know.

403
00:33:16,260 --> 00:33:17,320
SPEAKER_02: That's why I'm talking about that.

404
00:33:17,800 --> 00:33:18,820
SPEAKER_02: We don't need to rehash that.

405
00:33:19,100 --> 00:33:19,920
SPEAKER_01: That was a citation.

406
00:33:20,200 --> 00:33:20,640
SPEAKER_02: Exactly.

407
00:33:21,220 --> 00:33:22,820
SPEAKER_00: Oh, that's what you're saying.

408
00:33:23,060 --> 00:33:23,520
SPEAKER_00: Wow, sorry.

409
00:33:24,020 --> 00:33:24,420
SPEAKER_02: Keep up, man.

410
00:33:24,840 --> 00:33:26,120
SPEAKER_00: You're referencing the episode title.

411
00:33:26,800 --> 00:33:29,160
SPEAKER_00: I thought you were saying the thing that we named the episode after.

412
00:33:30,520 --> 00:33:30,920
SPEAKER_02: It was both.

413
00:33:31,660 --> 00:33:31,960
SPEAKER_00: Okay.

414
00:33:32,700 --> 00:33:34,160
SPEAKER_00: Lubas Pastor has research on this.

415
00:33:34,580 --> 00:33:48,440
SPEAKER_00: We had an episode of him years ago, but other academics have looked at it too, that in theory, the size of the active management industry matters, where if it gets too small, if indexing gets too big, in theory, there's a point where maybe active has a chance to come back.

416
00:33:49,020 --> 00:33:51,960
SPEAKER_00: It is like an equilibrium and that's like Grossman Stiglitz paradox stuff.

417
00:33:52,000 --> 00:33:54,100
SPEAKER_00: There's a point where there's not enough active.

418
00:33:54,520 --> 00:34:01,800
SPEAKER_00: If we reach that point, in theory, active should start outperforming, which would then drive dollars back toward active and we'll get back to the equilibrium.

419
00:34:02,340 --> 00:34:09,880
SPEAKER_01: Which is just a kind of extension of the way that saying indexing will always be average preferable.

420
00:34:10,260 --> 00:34:19,480
SPEAKER_01: There can never be a point at least not for any period of time where there is so much indexing that active becomes advantageous.

421
00:34:19,699 --> 00:34:26,300
SPEAKER_01: That might happen for some theoretical short period but there must always be an equilibrium that it returns to.

422
00:34:27,400 --> 00:34:28,500
SPEAKER_00: I agree with that.

423
00:34:28,540 --> 00:34:34,580
SPEAKER_00: The next obvious question I think, we're kind of dancing around it just now, is whether you can identify those big winners ahead of time.

424
00:34:35,040 --> 00:34:41,380
SPEAKER_00: I think a lot of people look to active funds that have beaten the market in the past and think they're going to continue performing in the future.

425
00:34:41,420 --> 00:34:43,020
SPEAKER_00: That's another episode I want to do.

426
00:34:43,159 --> 00:34:46,080
SPEAKER_00: actually, is I've looked at some active funds that have long history.

427
00:34:46,199 --> 00:34:51,199
SPEAKER_00: Someone sent me once, they were like, hey, I'm being pitched on these funds and they do have great performance histories, can you look at them?

428
00:34:51,880 --> 00:34:53,620
SPEAKER_00: I looked at them, they're like, oh, they've actually done really well.

429
00:34:53,980 --> 00:34:57,100
SPEAKER_00: They've got positive five factor alphas, wow, these are impressive funds.

430
00:34:57,160 --> 00:35:02,780
SPEAKER_00: But then I started slicing the data up, they had a really good starting period.

431
00:35:03,220 --> 00:35:04,940
SPEAKER_00: they had a really good period somewhere in the middle.

432
00:35:05,500 --> 00:35:07,520
SPEAKER_00: But other than that, the fund has not done well.

433
00:35:08,100 --> 00:35:12,660
SPEAKER_00: So if you take out those whatever, like eight really good years of performance, the rest of the history of the fund is not so great.

434
00:35:13,340 --> 00:35:14,620
SPEAKER_00: I think that'd be an interesting thing to look at.

435
00:35:14,740 --> 00:35:19,720
SPEAKER_00: Can we find active funds with really good long track records and then think about how many investors have actually benefited from that?

436
00:35:20,400 --> 00:35:20,900
SPEAKER_02: That's just it.

437
00:35:21,340 --> 00:35:23,960
SPEAKER_02: Most people didn't own the funds back then because there wasn't a track record.

438
00:35:24,020 --> 00:35:28,060
SPEAKER_02: So to capture the outperformance, you're basically taking a bit of a leap of faith on these funds.

439
00:35:28,560 --> 00:35:32,620
SPEAKER_02: And advisors are notorious for pretending they totally would have had your money in these funds right from the beginning.

440
00:35:32,860 --> 00:35:35,500
SPEAKER_02: They'll pitch you these funds, look, this is how we invest and look how well they've done.

441
00:35:36,280 --> 00:35:44,140
SPEAKER_02: But if you actually look at their client portfolios, it's highly unlikely that they've actually invested their client money in that exact same mix of funds for that length of period of time.

442
00:35:44,540 --> 00:35:51,740
SPEAKER_02: Really what they're doing is just sorting a Morningstar filter by recent performance for the most part and being like, oh, for sure, this is how all of our clients have performed.

443
00:35:52,200 --> 00:35:53,880
SPEAKER_02: Not everybody, but it's largely untrue.

444
00:35:54,420 --> 00:36:00,220
SPEAKER_01: One of the nuances on that front two in terms of persistence of performance that I thought was really interesting.

445
00:36:00,320 --> 00:36:04,000
SPEAKER_01: And I don't have the data in front of me, but there was some evidence.

446
00:36:04,080 --> 00:36:13,140
SPEAKER_01: My understanding is if, for example, you look back at funds that outperformed over the last 10 years, would they continue to outperform over the next 10 years?

447
00:36:13,180 --> 00:36:15,000
SPEAKER_01: And as we know, the answer is typically no.

448
00:36:15,820 --> 00:36:24,120
SPEAKER_01: But funds in the lowest quartile or decile of worst performance, actually that was something of a predictor.

449
00:36:24,640 --> 00:36:25,580
SPEAKER_01: of future performance.

450
00:36:25,620 --> 00:36:28,920
SPEAKER_01: In other words, bad funds continued to be bad.

451
00:36:29,100 --> 00:36:34,560
SPEAKER_01: There was no reversion to the mean like you would expect with an index fund, for example.

452
00:36:35,160 --> 00:36:38,480
SPEAKER_01: You could have an unskilled manager who charges high fees.

453
00:36:38,520 --> 00:36:45,860
SPEAKER_01: I think you can say with confidence that you are likely to experience persistent underperformance with that formula.

454
00:36:46,320 --> 00:36:48,840
SPEAKER_01: It doesn't necessarily work equally both ways.

455
00:36:49,760 --> 00:36:50,600
SPEAKER_00: I have not seen that one.

456
00:36:50,720 --> 00:36:56,520
SPEAKER_00: I have seen a three-year study that looks at the past three-year winners, losers and neutral.

457
00:36:56,660 --> 00:37:02,040
SPEAKER_00: I don't know what neutral was, but it was funds that outperformed, funds that underperformed and some middle group.

458
00:37:02,100 --> 00:37:07,620
SPEAKER_00: and then they looked at how do they perform over the next three years and the losers outperformed the winners by quite a bit.

459
00:37:07,940 --> 00:37:11,320
SPEAKER_00: I don't know if they make an argument for why they see that, but then there's another paper.

460
00:37:11,360 --> 00:37:15,360
SPEAKER_00: I don't know what the time period is, but they look at valuations of fund holdings.

461
00:37:15,660 --> 00:37:21,920
SPEAKER_00: If a fund has done well recently, it tends to have stocks with higher valuations and that explains why those funds.

462
00:37:22,340 --> 00:37:24,020
SPEAKER_00: than have struggles in the future.

463
00:37:24,740 --> 00:37:29,940
SPEAKER_01: Yeah, I think you'd really have to dig into the details of what was the explanation for the underperformance.

464
00:37:30,320 --> 00:37:36,560
SPEAKER_01: If it was just poor stock picking and high fees, that would be something that would persist.

465
00:37:36,980 --> 00:37:47,860
SPEAKER_01: But if it was just something like you had an excellent value manager during a period where value stocks underperformed, that wasn't necessarily lack of skill or high fees that caused underperformance.

466
00:37:48,480 --> 00:37:52,380
SPEAKER_01: And when value stocks recover, presumably that manager would do better.

467
00:37:53,000 --> 00:37:53,700
SPEAKER_01: It is interesting.

468
00:37:53,760 --> 00:38:03,940
SPEAKER_01: It does kind of go back to the comment about Morningstar saying that if you sorted just on fees, that would be a pretty decent proxy for predicting returns going forward.

469
00:38:04,360 --> 00:38:05,680
SPEAKER_00: Best in mind, it does look at fees.

470
00:38:05,740 --> 00:38:08,160
SPEAKER_00: They say in the paper, they don't find a super strong relationship.

471
00:38:08,380 --> 00:38:11,920
SPEAKER_00: when you visually inspect the chart that shows that analysis.

472
00:38:12,580 --> 00:38:14,040
SPEAKER_00: There's some relationship like the higher fee.

473
00:38:14,100 --> 00:38:17,280
SPEAKER_00: funds definitely do worse, but it's not a perfect monotonic relationship.

474
00:38:18,420 --> 00:38:20,080
SPEAKER_00: Back to this idea of persistence.

475
00:38:20,120 --> 00:38:26,580
SPEAKER_00: Can we find funds that are going to do well in the future based on how well they've done in the past.

476
00:38:27,480 --> 00:38:28,860
SPEAKER_00: Not a lot of evidence that that's true.

477
00:38:29,320 --> 00:38:35,700
SPEAKER_00: Funds that have done well in prior periods do not tend to continue doing well in future periods.

478
00:38:36,200 --> 00:38:38,580
SPEAKER_00: There are two potential explanations for this.

479
00:38:39,260 --> 00:38:48,640
SPEAKER_00: One is from the 1997 Mark Carhartt paper, which he says in the conclusion that the data do not support the existence of skilled or informed mutual fund portfolio managers.

480
00:38:49,340 --> 00:38:53,620
SPEAKER_00: Basically, managers who were successful were just lucky in the past and then their luck runs out.

481
00:38:54,040 --> 00:38:58,540
SPEAKER_00: That's one explanation that there's just no skill and it's all random.

482
00:38:59,300 --> 00:39:02,680
SPEAKER_00: Because it's random, you can't bet on what happened in the past repeating in the future.

483
00:39:03,140 --> 00:39:10,140
SPEAKER_00: The other possible explanation, which seems theoretically nicer because you can't imagine that there's just no skill.

484
00:39:10,440 --> 00:39:12,040
SPEAKER_00: People in finance are really smart.

485
00:39:12,500 --> 00:39:17,460
SPEAKER_00: Finance probably attracts too many smart people that should be doing other things that are productive for society.

486
00:39:18,400 --> 00:39:30,720
SPEAKER_00: The other possible explanation is, and this is from Van Binsbergen, which you can listen to them explain this in episode 220 if you want to, is the mutual fund managers are indeed skilled, but their skill does not translate to higher returns for fund investors.

487
00:39:31,100 --> 00:39:39,880
SPEAKER_00: Instead, assets flow into the funds of skilled managers right up to the point where the fund gets too big or just big enough where the manager can't keep outperforming.

488
00:39:39,920 --> 00:39:43,600
SPEAKER_00: They can't keep generating alpha due to diseconomies of scale.

489
00:39:44,020 --> 00:39:45,040
SPEAKER_00: It's an equilibrium result.

490
00:39:45,180 --> 00:39:55,480
SPEAKER_00: The result is that The most skilled managers earn huge fees by having large funds because if you've got more skill, you can absorb more assets before you're not able to beat the market anymore.

491
00:39:56,000 --> 00:40:02,360
SPEAKER_00: But the benefits of the manager's skill accrues to the manager because a more skilled manager can have a bigger fund, which means they're going to earn more fees.

492
00:40:02,940 --> 00:40:05,020
SPEAKER_00: It does not accrue to the investors as alpha.

493
00:40:05,260 --> 00:40:12,320
SPEAKER_00: The only way to find alpha is to pick a manager who has not yet been filled up with assets to the point where they can't outperform.

494
00:40:13,080 --> 00:40:15,000
SPEAKER_00: It's just like identifying undervalued stock.

495
00:40:15,080 --> 00:40:18,400
SPEAKER_00: You have to identify an undervalued manager if you want alpha.

496
00:40:18,760 --> 00:40:22,520
SPEAKER_00: Otherwise, you just get returns in line with the risk of the assets of the manager invested.

497
00:40:23,040 --> 00:40:25,980
SPEAKER_01: That's a really elegant explanation, I have to say.

498
00:40:26,340 --> 00:40:28,580
SPEAKER_01: It makes perfect intuitive sense.

499
00:40:29,040 --> 00:40:30,340
SPEAKER_01: In the real world, we've seen it.

500
00:40:30,460 --> 00:40:37,560
SPEAKER_01: There's so many of the best funds that have had some period of significant outperformance.

501
00:40:37,720 --> 00:40:38,160
SPEAKER_01: What do they do?

502
00:40:38,200 --> 00:40:40,460
SPEAKER_01: They close the funds to new investors.

503
00:40:40,720 --> 00:40:41,240
SPEAKER_01: They have to.

504
00:40:41,940 --> 00:40:44,920
SPEAKER_01: It's related to what we talked about in terms of concentration.

505
00:40:45,520 --> 00:40:51,120
SPEAKER_01: You don't create a fund with great outperformance by buying an index-like portfolio.

506
00:40:51,820 --> 00:40:53,720
SPEAKER_01: It's one thing if you're managing $100 million.

507
00:40:54,200 --> 00:40:56,580
SPEAKER_01: It's another thing if you're managing $200 billion.

508
00:40:57,620 --> 00:41:04,640
SPEAKER_01: Obviously, you cannot possibly scale up your insights and your ideas at that level.

509
00:41:05,080 --> 00:41:06,380
SPEAKER_01: Maybe even 100 million is too much.

510
00:41:06,460 --> 00:41:06,900
SPEAKER_01: I don't know.

511
00:41:07,060 --> 00:41:20,340
SPEAKER_01: But the point is that it makes perfect sense that any truly skilled manager with an expectation about performance must have a finite limit of how much money it can put into play.

512
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:21,320
SPEAKER_00: For sure.

513
00:41:21,700 --> 00:41:22,200
SPEAKER_00: Look at Buffett.

514
00:41:22,360 --> 00:41:23,160
SPEAKER_00: Buffett talks about this.

515
00:41:23,820 --> 00:41:25,540
SPEAKER_00: He literally says, this is what has happened.

516
00:41:25,580 --> 00:41:27,680
SPEAKER_00: This is why Berkshire is performing the way that it is.

517
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:28,520
SPEAKER_01: Exactly.

518
00:41:29,140 --> 00:41:30,180
SPEAKER_01: Really interesting paper.

519
00:41:30,880 --> 00:41:31,800
SPEAKER_00: Yeah, that's a cool one.

520
00:41:32,140 --> 00:41:43,720
SPEAKER_00: In either case, whether it's luck or diseconomies of scale, the empirical reality and this comes from academic studies like the ones we talked about but The industry report we mentioned earlier, it also does a version of this where they look at persistence.

521
00:41:44,160 --> 00:41:49,160
SPEAKER_00: Wherever you look, there's not a whole lot of evidence that funds that have done well in the past will continue to do well in the future.

522
00:41:49,340 --> 00:41:53,720
SPEAKER_00: I think this is important because there are always going to be funds that have done well in the past.

523
00:41:54,140 --> 00:42:01,140
SPEAKER_00: We could go look right now and find, I don't know how many, a bunch of mutual funds that have done incredibly well over the last 20, 25, even 30 years.

524
00:42:01,780 --> 00:42:09,040
SPEAKER_00: That's always going to be the case, but that doesn't really matter because it doesn't tell us anything about how that fund is going to do in the future.

525
00:42:09,700 --> 00:42:14,760
SPEAKER_00: I think it's a tool for investors to understand that just because a fund has done well in the past doesn't mean it's going to do well in the future.

526
00:42:14,800 --> 00:42:25,580
SPEAKER_00: It's really, really valuable because you'll always be presented with look at this fund, it's beaten the market for the last whatever, five, 10 years but that does not give you a whole lot of information about how it's going to perform in the future.

527
00:42:26,220 --> 00:42:32,580
SPEAKER_02: I think the other thing that people often don't realize is maybe there's luck in the actual stock picking but there's also luck in terms of sectors.

528
00:42:33,160 --> 00:42:38,360
SPEAKER_02: Somebody sent me a comment this morning that they were presented with, their advisor got them something like 39%.

529
00:42:38,740 --> 00:42:40,600
SPEAKER_02: last year, the last year before that, or whatever.

530
00:42:40,980 --> 00:42:41,680
SPEAKER_02: They must be great.

531
00:42:41,740 --> 00:42:44,960
SPEAKER_02: And it's like, well, no, they were basically invested in the equivalent of the NASDAQ.

532
00:42:45,000 --> 00:42:47,000
SPEAKER_02: It's like a science and technology fund or something like that.

533
00:42:47,220 --> 00:42:49,780
SPEAKER_02: So they're benefiting from the rise in that sector altogether.

534
00:42:50,280 --> 00:42:51,640
SPEAKER_02: That beat the overall market, yes.

535
00:42:51,760 --> 00:43:00,320
SPEAKER_02: But were they lucky in terms of the place in time that they were invested in those sectors, or were they lucky in the actual individual stock picking that was going on within the funds themselves?

536
00:43:00,580 --> 00:43:02,640
SPEAKER_02: These days, you look at everyone, everyone's like, oh, 100% NASDAQ.

537
00:43:03,040 --> 00:43:03,340
SPEAKER_01: Well, why?

538
00:43:03,540 --> 00:43:04,780
SPEAKER_02: Well, because it went up a lot last year.

539
00:43:05,260 --> 00:43:08,640
SPEAKER_02: People think they get market beating returns by just overexposing themselves to a particular sector.

540
00:43:08,680 --> 00:43:09,540
SPEAKER_02: that's done really, really well.

541
00:43:10,080 --> 00:43:17,980
SPEAKER_02: I think that those who are essentially trying to find skilled managers might think they found a skilled manager when it was actually just a mutual fund whose mandate was to invest in a particular sector.

542
00:43:18,040 --> 00:43:18,820
SPEAKER_02: that did incredibly well.

543
00:43:19,100 --> 00:43:21,460
SPEAKER_01: To play devil's advocate on that, that makes sense.

544
00:43:21,520 --> 00:43:30,140
SPEAKER_01: if your mandate is you're a technology fund and you must invest in technology stocks because that's what your mandate is.

545
00:43:30,860 --> 00:43:38,120
SPEAKER_01: Even if they fall out of favor, you still are compelled to invest in that sector because that's what people are buying your fund for.

546
00:43:38,780 --> 00:43:56,780
SPEAKER_01: But to look at the other side, how would you respond if I said, maybe part of the skill of the active manager who has a much broader mandate, US equities period, knows when to move into technology and take advantage of that and knows when to get out before it reverts to the mean.

547
00:43:57,400 --> 00:44:10,180
SPEAKER_01: Is there any evidence of persistent skill in terms of sector rotation or other sort of tactical asset allocation that isn't stock picking but moves in and out according to a much broader mandate.

548
00:44:10,760 --> 00:44:12,240
SPEAKER_00: I don't think tactical funds do very well.

549
00:44:12,660 --> 00:44:30,840
SPEAKER_00: The craziest stories of fund managers that do insanely well, multiple 100% returns in a year or even over a couple of years in some cases, followed by just an absolute crash where investors lose most of their capital, most of those are sector specific active managers.

550
00:44:31,300 --> 00:44:35,300
SPEAKER_00: Internet dot com era managers like that, Kathy Wood was like that.

551
00:44:35,920 --> 00:44:37,280
SPEAKER_00: One sector was doing really well.

552
00:44:37,700 --> 00:44:41,300
SPEAKER_00: They were making the right bets in that sector, so the returns were just insane.

553
00:44:41,960 --> 00:44:46,200
SPEAKER_00: But then the bottom often falls out because valuations were just out of control.

554
00:44:46,740 --> 00:44:47,740
SPEAKER_00: So definitely stories like that.

555
00:44:48,280 --> 00:44:52,940
SPEAKER_00: I remember when ARC was happening, that was a really hard one for investors to ignore.

556
00:44:53,380 --> 00:44:55,360
SPEAKER_00: We forget about how, man, the psychology is crazy.

557
00:44:55,440 --> 00:45:01,440
SPEAKER_00: Forget about how tempting it is when you see the returns of something like the ARC fund or funds.

558
