605
00:48:12,280 --> 00:48:13,420
SPEAKER_00: Anyway, that was a total digression.

606
00:48:13,480 --> 00:48:15,640
SPEAKER_00: Didn't plan to talk about ARC, but here we are.

607
00:48:15,700 --> 00:48:16,840
SPEAKER_00: I think it is important though.

608
00:48:17,420 --> 00:48:18,880
SPEAKER_01: Well, we're talking about persistence.

609
00:48:19,200 --> 00:48:26,500
SPEAKER_01: It's just a really easiest example of that and one of the most dramatic examples of that, that most of us will remember.

610
00:48:27,140 --> 00:48:27,380
SPEAKER_00: True.

611
00:48:27,960 --> 00:48:30,880
SPEAKER_00: I've heard people ask, and this is not a thing that I'm coming up with.

612
00:48:31,260 --> 00:48:35,540
SPEAKER_00: Other people have said this before, but I've heard people ask why you would settle for average returns with index funds.

613
00:48:35,840 --> 00:48:37,880
SPEAKER_00: Why would you want the market average when you could try and beat it?

614
00:48:38,320 --> 00:48:49,000
SPEAKER_00: You look at the data on fund performance, even on investor performance, index funds are beating the vast majority of active funds and the vast majority of individual investors.

615
00:48:49,620 --> 00:48:50,940
SPEAKER_00: Are they really average returns?

616
00:48:51,400 --> 00:48:52,320
SPEAKER_00: They're market returns.

617
00:48:52,980 --> 00:48:53,080
SPEAKER_01: Yeah.

618
00:48:53,160 --> 00:48:55,400
SPEAKER_01: I think it's a misunderstanding of average.

619
00:48:55,700 --> 00:48:56,840
SPEAKER_01: I made this point in my book.

620
00:48:57,100 --> 00:49:04,900
SPEAKER_01: If you think as an indexer, if you use an indexing strategy throughout your investing lifetime, that your returns will be average.

621
00:49:05,280 --> 00:49:14,580
SPEAKER_01: I mean, if you do it with discipline, you will likely outperform 80 to 90% of other investors and that's not average.

622
00:49:15,020 --> 00:49:15,720
SPEAKER_01: You're a superstar.

623
00:49:16,320 --> 00:49:22,920
SPEAKER_01: market average is not the same as you are just average in a large field of investors, right?

624
00:49:22,980 --> 00:49:24,100
SPEAKER_01: It's exceptional.

625
00:49:24,700 --> 00:49:25,660
SPEAKER_02: Well, they take it personally.

626
00:49:26,060 --> 00:49:28,040
SPEAKER_02: Being average just feels underwhelming.

627
00:49:28,340 --> 00:49:30,080
SPEAKER_02: That's to your point just absolutely not the case.

628
00:49:30,120 --> 00:49:34,120
SPEAKER_02: We're not saying that you're an average person in terms of your skill set or anything.

629
00:49:34,360 --> 00:49:42,340
SPEAKER_02: Your returns will be average on a gross basis and to your point, NHL quality superstar compared to your peers on a net of return basis.

630
00:49:43,160 --> 00:49:48,780
SPEAKER_00: Maybe I have one cousin that gets 40% a year in ARK at least over one period of time and then you might feel bad.

631
00:49:49,640 --> 00:49:52,220
SPEAKER_02: Once or twice but we'll never show you his statements.

632
00:49:53,080 --> 00:49:56,120
SPEAKER_02: We'll never back it up with actual statements but we'll tell you about it.

633
00:49:56,760 --> 00:49:57,020
SPEAKER_00: True.

634
00:49:57,460 --> 00:50:01,220
SPEAKER_00: There's a study that I'm going to try and do a video on individual stock picking.

635
00:50:01,280 --> 00:50:03,740
SPEAKER_00: I did one of those years ago, I want to do kind of an updated one.

636
00:50:04,420 --> 00:50:06,160
SPEAKER_00: There's a study I found when I was researching that.

637
00:50:06,460 --> 00:50:11,540
SPEAKER_00: I don't remember the statistics in there but the gap between how investors appraise their returns.

638
00:50:11,840 --> 00:50:13,620
SPEAKER_00: If I say, Mark, what have your returns been?

639
00:50:14,180 --> 00:50:14,520
SPEAKER_00: you tell me.

640
00:50:14,760 --> 00:50:16,680
SPEAKER_00: Then I take your statements and I actually audit them.

641
00:50:17,140 --> 00:50:22,000
SPEAKER_00: The gap between those two numbers is massive, where investors dramatically overestimate what their returns are.

642
00:50:22,500 --> 00:50:22,860
SPEAKER_02: I believe it.

643
00:50:23,540 --> 00:50:26,260
SPEAKER_00: Next point on index funds, they're tax efficient.

644
00:50:26,740 --> 00:50:34,820
SPEAKER_00: More trading inside of an active fund tends to lead to more taxable distributions, which adds a pretty significant additional drag on long-term returns for taxable investors.

645
00:50:35,140 --> 00:50:40,040
SPEAKER_00: We talked about transaction costs earlier, but all of those transactions can also lead to taxable distributions.

646
00:50:40,800 --> 00:50:47,340
SPEAKER_00: less of an issue for US listed active ETFs but here in Canada, whether it's a mutual fund or an ETF, this is going to be a problem.

647
00:50:47,540 --> 00:50:50,500
SPEAKER_00: We don't have the same mechanism that US ETFs have.

648
00:50:51,200 --> 00:51:05,860
SPEAKER_00: There is a paper comparing before and after tax returns of actively managed funds and index funds and it finds that however bad things look for active before taxes, it gets a whole lot worse relatively speaking after taxes because index funds are more tax efficient.

649
00:51:06,360 --> 00:51:07,320
SPEAKER_00: That's tax efficiency.

650
00:51:07,900 --> 00:51:12,260
SPEAKER_00: Another one is simplicity and I think this is probably one of the most overlooked benefits.

651
00:51:12,660 --> 00:51:18,060
SPEAKER_00: If you invest in active funds and this is even true for factor funds, not just traditional active.

652
00:51:18,640 --> 00:51:21,960
SPEAKER_00: If you invest in active funds, it is hard to know how you're doing.

653
00:51:22,460 --> 00:51:25,440
SPEAKER_00: I talked with this on Coffeezilla too because he was asking me about factor investing.

654
00:51:25,480 --> 00:51:28,940
SPEAKER_00: It was supposed to be a podcast for beginners and he asked about factor investing.

655
00:51:29,020 --> 00:51:30,400
SPEAKER_00: I don't know if that was the right thing to talk about.

656
00:51:30,700 --> 00:51:33,920
SPEAKER_00: With active, traditional active, is the manager doing what they're supposed to be doing?

657
00:51:34,580 --> 00:51:35,880
SPEAKER_00: Have they lost their edge?

658
00:51:35,920 --> 00:51:38,040
SPEAKER_00: Has their fund gotten too big like we talked about earlier?

659
00:51:38,520 --> 00:51:41,840
SPEAKER_00: But then with factors too, are these factors still relevant?

660
00:51:41,880 --> 00:51:42,660
SPEAKER_00: Are these the right ones?

661
00:51:42,820 --> 00:51:45,180
SPEAKER_00: Do we need to care about the new research that just came out?

662
00:51:45,360 --> 00:51:49,060
SPEAKER_00: Do we need to care about Andrew Chen's research that says that there are no factor premiums after costs?

663
00:51:49,780 --> 00:51:54,500
SPEAKER_00: That's all stuff that you have to think about and worry about and it makes it hard to stay invested and stay disciplined.

664
00:51:54,560 --> 00:51:58,320
SPEAKER_00: I think at least on the factor investing side, there's a little bit more theory and evidence.

665
00:51:58,900 --> 00:52:03,560
SPEAKER_00: I'll let indexing to back up what you're doing so it's maybe easier than traditional active to stick with.

666
00:52:04,020 --> 00:52:05,820
SPEAKER_00: Still, it is something to think about.

667
00:52:06,380 --> 00:52:13,020
SPEAKER_00: With index funds, you can be pretty confident that you're going to earn the return of the index, net of some predictably low fees.

668
00:52:13,640 --> 00:52:14,540
SPEAKER_00: You know what you're going to get.

669
00:52:14,880 --> 00:52:16,640
SPEAKER_00: That should be relatively easy to stick with.

670
00:52:17,080 --> 00:52:25,980
SPEAKER_00: Now, there can be periods like the US last decade where US stocks return nothing for a US investor over a 10-year period.

671
00:52:26,440 --> 00:52:28,440
SPEAKER_00: I'm sure that would be difficult to stick with.

672
00:52:28,480 --> 00:52:30,660
SPEAKER_00: If you're globally diversified, maybe it's not so bad.

673
00:52:31,180 --> 00:52:38,220
SPEAKER_00: I'll be interested to hear how all of the US investors who don't think you need international diversification feel if there's another US lost decade.

674
00:52:38,620 --> 00:52:39,420
SPEAKER_00: We'll see how that goes.

675
00:52:39,980 --> 00:52:40,980
SPEAKER_00: That's a big one, simplicity.

676
00:52:41,780 --> 00:52:47,980
SPEAKER_00: Something else that's related to the other stuff, related to simplicity and the costs, you keep more of your returns by doing less stuff.

677
00:52:48,720 --> 00:52:50,060
SPEAKER_00: I think this is Charlie Ellis' point.

678
00:52:50,400 --> 00:52:52,580
SPEAKER_00: He was on an episode 244 if you want to check that out.

679
00:52:53,280 --> 00:53:00,400
SPEAKER_00: He talks about winners games where the outcome is decided by the winner and losers games where the outcome is decided by the loser.

680
00:53:01,020 --> 00:53:06,580
SPEAKER_00: He talks about tennis in his paper where professional tennis is a winner's game.

681
00:53:06,640 --> 00:53:08,300
SPEAKER_00: The winner wins by being better.

682
00:53:09,340 --> 00:53:12,820
SPEAKER_00: Amateur tennis is a loser's game where the winner wins by making fewer mistakes.

683
00:53:13,500 --> 00:53:14,500
SPEAKER_00: That's the main idea.

684
00:53:14,640 --> 00:53:23,320
SPEAKER_00: Winning a winner's game requires exerting effort being better to win while winning a loser's game requires basically minimizing your mistakes and doing less.

685
00:53:23,840 --> 00:53:26,080
SPEAKER_00: He says that investing is a loser's game.

686
00:53:26,780 --> 00:53:34,180
SPEAKER_00: One of his prescriptions is to make fewer mistakes is to keep things simple and index funds, they accomplish that better than really anything.

687
00:53:34,720 --> 00:53:40,820
SPEAKER_01: That's one of my favorite insights in the index fund literature and that goes back to the 70s.

688
00:53:41,280 --> 00:53:52,200
SPEAKER_01: It's so true and this is really hard I think for investors to understand on an intuitive level is that investment returns are not something that you have to go out and hunt and kill and drag home.

689
00:53:52,540 --> 00:53:57,780
SPEAKER_01: Investment returns fall from the sky and it's up to you to capture them.

690
00:53:58,440 --> 00:54:04,620
SPEAKER_01: It's not about doing more, it's about putting a great plan in place and then doing less.

691
00:54:04,840 --> 00:54:13,700
SPEAKER_01: I think anybody who has either worked in the industry and kind of seen all of this come down or talked to a lot of investors eventually comes to this.

692
00:54:13,820 --> 00:54:18,640
SPEAKER_01: But that is not an insight that you will get the first time you read Charlie Ellis' book.

693
00:54:19,100 --> 00:54:26,020
SPEAKER_01: Probably your brain will resist the idea because so much of our culture portrays it.

694
00:54:26,060 --> 00:54:32,440
SPEAKER_01: investing is something that you really need to go out and know a lot about in order to get those returns.

695
00:54:33,060 --> 00:54:45,740
SPEAKER_01: We've all talked about when we look at people like employer plans, retirement plans, or people who just pick a target date fund, contribute biweekly for 15 years, never look at it, and retire wealthy.

696
00:54:45,780 --> 00:54:48,820
SPEAKER_01: That's a great example of winning the losers game.

697
00:54:48,860 --> 00:54:51,260
SPEAKER_01: You just didn't make any mistakes along the way.

698
00:54:51,700 --> 00:54:54,840
SPEAKER_01: It wasn't that you had amazing investment skills.

699
00:54:54,980 --> 00:54:57,440
SPEAKER_01: It was just, you didn't get in the way of yourself.

700
00:54:58,000 --> 00:55:02,640
SPEAKER_00: Ellis says in there in that paper, if you can't beat the market, you certainly should consider joining it.

701
00:55:03,060 --> 00:55:07,220
SPEAKER_00: An index fund is one way and he wrote, keeping in mind this is 1975.

702
00:55:07,840 --> 00:55:12,860
SPEAKER_00: The data from the performance measurement firms show that an index fund would have outperformed most money managers.

703
00:55:13,320 --> 00:55:18,080
SPEAKER_00: Obviously has not changed a whole lot, which is interesting to think about that.

704
00:55:18,460 --> 00:55:24,900
SPEAKER_00: That's been pretty stable over time going back to 1945 when the 1968 Jensen paper looked at the data.

705
00:55:25,400 --> 00:55:32,260
SPEAKER_00: The last point I want to make on the case for index funds is that index funds are consistent with foundational finance theory.

706
00:55:33,060 --> 00:55:34,320
SPEAKER_00: I love this point personally.

707
00:55:34,520 --> 00:55:38,720
SPEAKER_00: I think it just puts such a nice bow on everything, on all of the data that we've talked about.

708
00:55:38,760 --> 00:55:40,440
SPEAKER_00: The data really support the theory.

709
00:55:40,940 --> 00:55:44,600
SPEAKER_00: It's very nice that such strong theory does back this approach to investing.

710
00:55:45,220 --> 00:55:57,140
SPEAKER_00: So Harry Markowitz developed modern portfolio theory in the 1950s on the basis that optimal portfolios minimize variance for a given level of expected return or maximize expected return for a given level of variance, two sides of the same coin.

711
00:55:57,820 --> 00:55:59,720
SPEAKER_00: That's accomplished through diversification.

712
00:56:00,460 --> 00:56:05,720
SPEAKER_00: Markowitz basically showed mathematically why diversification is so important, which was a big step forward in investing.

713
00:56:06,280 --> 00:56:15,900
SPEAKER_00: Then Bill Sharp's 1964 capital asset pricing model or the CAPM, turned Markowitz theory into a testable prediction about the relationship between risk and expected return.

714
00:56:16,420 --> 00:56:21,580
SPEAKER_00: In the CAPM, each asset's price is based on its contribution to the risk and expected return of the overall market.

715
00:56:22,220 --> 00:56:26,440
SPEAKER_00: I gave us a model to think about expected returns which did not previously exist.

716
00:56:26,960 --> 00:56:36,760
SPEAKER_00: One of the big insights from the CAPM is that in an efficient market, the market capitalization weighted total market portfolio is the portfolio with the optimal risk and expected return trade off.

717
00:56:37,380 --> 00:56:42,260
SPEAKER_00: That must be true because each asset is priced such that that is true in an efficient market.

718
00:56:42,780 --> 00:56:43,740
SPEAKER_00: That's obviously a big question.

719
00:56:43,860 --> 00:56:44,700
SPEAKER_00: Are markets efficient?

720
00:56:45,300 --> 00:56:48,300
SPEAKER_00: That's not something that's answerable because of the joint hypothesis problem.

721
00:56:48,900 --> 00:56:50,240
SPEAKER_00: It's always going to be an ongoing debate.

722
00:56:50,660 --> 00:57:02,120
SPEAKER_00: But Eugene Fama's work on market efficiency, which started in 1960s and continues to today, suggests that markets are efficient enough that most investors should act as if they are, even if perfect market efficiency is an unrealistic ideal.

723
00:57:02,760 --> 00:57:06,400
SPEAKER_00: To be clear here, perfect market efficiency is not something that even Fama believes it.

724
00:57:06,700 --> 00:57:10,980
SPEAKER_00: He'll laugh if you ask them if markets are efficient and they'll say, well, they can't be perfectly efficient.

725
00:57:11,640 --> 00:57:24,280
SPEAKER_00: On this podcast, when we had Fama on, we asked what the best test for market efficiency is and he said that from the perspective of investors, the fact that the pre-fee active mutual fund returns look roughly like what we would expect by random chance.

726
00:57:24,460 --> 00:57:28,140
SPEAKER_00: Well, net of fee active fund returns are a negative sum game, they're underperforming.

727
00:57:28,820 --> 00:57:30,580
SPEAKER_00: That's the strongest and most relevant evidence.

728
00:57:31,120 --> 00:57:36,040
SPEAKER_00: Kind of all the stuff that we talked about on active fund performance, lots of different ways to measure market efficiency.

729
00:57:36,720 --> 00:57:37,640
SPEAKER_00: many, many different ways.

730
00:57:38,240 --> 00:57:44,860
SPEAKER_00: But Fama is kind of saying from the perspective of investors, if active funds aren't being in the market, markets are efficient enough that you should just believe that they're efficient.

731
00:57:45,400 --> 00:57:51,580
SPEAKER_00: So you take all that together, Markowitz, Sharpe, Fama, all of whom are recipients of the Nobel Memorial Prize in economic sciences.

732
00:57:51,620 --> 00:58:06,000
SPEAKER_00: Their works suggest theoretically that most investors should just own the market through low cost index funds rather than paying high fees trying to beat the market, which of course is an assertion supported by the evidence that we went through earlier in the episode.

733
00:58:06,580 --> 00:58:07,940
